ORDINANCE NO. 8809

AN ORDINANCE UPGRADING THE MINIMUM QUALIFICATION STANDARD FOR
LOCAL ASSESSMENT OPERATIONS OFFICER POSITIONS UNDER THE LAND,
BUILDING AND MACHINERY APPRAISAL DIVISION IN THE DEPARTMENT OF
ASSESSMENT, MANILA

PREAMBLE

WHEREAS, Section 200 of Republic Act 7160, also known as the Local
Government Code of 1991, states that “the provinces and cities, including the municipalities within the Metropolitan Manila Area, shall be primarily responsible for the proper, efficient and effective administration of the real property tax”;

WHEREAS, the real property tax is undoubtedly a major potential source of revenue of the Local Government Unit (LGU) to finance its various priority programs and projects to improve its delivery of basic services to its constituents;

WHEREAS, the real property tax is the principal platform for raising revenues an influencing property development which will redound into greater interest and benefit to the City of Manila;

WHEREAS, each local government unit shall, as far as practicable, evolve progressive system of taxation;

WHEREAS, taxes are the lifeblood of the government and so should be collected without unnecessary hindrance. Without taxes, the government would be paralyzed for lack of motive to activate and operate it;

WHEREAS, to attain the vision of the City of Manila for gaining financial strength for real property development, fundamental reforms should be made in the real property tax administration;

WHEREAS, under the Local Government Code, the Assessor is empowered to
initiate, review and recommend changes in policies and objectives, plans and programs, techniques, procedures, and practices in the valuation and assessment of real properties for taxation purposes in accordance with RA 7160, The Philippine Valuation and Assessment Operations issued by the Department of Finance and other existing rules, regulations, and guidelines,

WHEREAS, Resolution No. 1201367 issued and promulgated by the Civil Service Commission on September 20, 2012, amended the qualification standards of the Assessor and Assistant Assessor requiring them to possess the eligibility under RA 1080 before they can be appointed to the position leaving behind the required minimum standards for the rank and file positions for Local Assessment Operations Officers
(LAOOs);

WHEREAS, for the proper administration of the real property services, there is also a need to upgrade the minimum qualification standards set for the positions of LAOOs in the Land, Building, and Machinery Appraisal Divisions of the Department of Assessment Manila, in addition to the requirements of the Civil Service Commission under Civil Service Commission Memorandum No. 14, Series of 2018 (2017 Omnibus Rules on Appointments and other Human Resource Actions-as amended 2019), to improve the quality of performance in the appraisal and assessment of real properties in the City of Manila as this is the bases of taxation and collection of realty taxes;

WHEREAS, professionalizing the real estate service will improve the accuracy quality, fairness, and transparency of valuations leading to greater confidence and reduce the financial risk of stakeholders: NOW, THEREFORE, 

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. This Ordinance shall be know as "An ordinance Upgrading the
Minimum Qualification Standards For Local Assessment Operations officer Positions Under the Land, Building and Machinery Appraisal Division in the Department of Assessment, Manila”.

SEC. 2. The position of Local Assessment Operations Officers under the Land, Building and Machinery Appraisal Division of the Department of Assessment up only by any person holding any of the following:
a. Board passer of Real Estate Service Act (RA 9646);
b. Board passer of Accountancy; 
c. Board passer of Architecture;
d. Board passer of Engineering; and
e. Graduate of Law (LLB/JD).

SEC. 3. In addition to the preceding section, the qualifications, powers, duties, and responsibilities of the herein positions shall be based on the provisions of the Local Government Code, Civil Service Commission (CSC), and other relevant laws.

SEC. 4. The employment and appointment of the individuals for the herein subject positions shall be within the qualifications standards, ad guidelines set in this Ordinance in addition to the requirements of the Civil Service Commission (CSC), and other relevant agencies.

SEC. 5. There shall be no additional funds necessary to immediately implement this Ordinance under the 2022 Executive Budget to provide funds for these positions.

SEC. 6. The report rendered by the Committee on Civil Service, Appointments and Reorganization shall be made part and parcel of this Ordinance. Any provisions of ordinances, executive orders, issuances, OF rules and regulations inconsistent with this Ordinance’s provisions are hereby repealed, amended, or modified accordingly.

SEC. 7. Effectivity Clause. — This Ordinance shall take effect upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on February 7, 2022.

ORDINANCE NO. 8803

AN ORDINANCE ESTABLISHING THE KALINGA SA MANILEÑO (KASAMA) PROGRAM AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, the COVID-19 pandemic has resulted in enormous job losses, financial difficulties, and poverty for many residents of the City of Manila;

WHEREAS, Section 9, Article II of the 1987 Constitution mandates the State to “promote a just and dynamic social order that will ensure the prosperity and independence of the nation and free the people from poverty through policies that provide adequate social services, promote full employment, a rising standard of living, and an improved quality of life for all”;

WHEREAS, Section 16 of Republic Act No. 7160, otherwise known as the Local Government Code of 1991, mandates local government units to ensure and support, among other things, economic prosperity and social justice, and the promotion of full employment among their residents;

WHEREAS, the same law empowers local government units to exercise the powers expressly granted, those necessarily implied therefrom, as well as those necessary, appropriate, or incidental for efficient and effective governance and the promotion of general welfare;

WHEREAS, the Manila City PESO (Public Employment Service Office) has launched the KASAMA Program, a community-based assistance program providing emergency employment for displaced workers, underemployed, and seasonal workers within the City of Manila, for a minimum of 10 days and up to a maximum of 40 days, depending on the nature of the work to be performed;

WHEREAS, one of the goals of the KASAMA Program is to help deter poverty and economic inequality within the City of Manila by providing a source of income to poor, vulnerable, and marginalized workers: NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:
SECTION 1. Establishment of the Kalinga sa Manileño Program; Description — There is hereby established the Kalinga sa Manileño (KASAMA) Program which is a community-based assistance program providing emergency employment for displaced workers, underemployed and seasonal workers within the City of Manila, for a minimum period of 10 days, but not to exceed a maximum of 40 days, depending on the nature of work to be performed.

SEC. 2. Objectives — The KASAMA Program aims to contribute to the reduction of poverty and economic inequality within the City of Manila by providing temporary sources of income to poor, vulnerable, and marginalized workers.

SEC. 3. Implementing Office — The program shall be implemented by the Public Employment Service Office (PESO) and other relevant departments, bureaus, and offices of the City of Manila.

SEC. 4. Qualified Beneficiaries – Persons joining the KASAMA Program must meet the following qualifications: a) At least 18 years old; b) A bona fide resident of the City of Manila; and c) Not be employed in any private or public institution.

SEC. 5. Eligible Projects — Projects that would qualify under the KASAMA Program are:
a.        Social community projects, such as repair, maintenance, and improvement of public facilities and infrastructure such as schools and health centers, debris clearing, canal de-clogging, debris segregation and materials recovery, stockpiling, and clearing, among others;

b.        Economic community projects like repair, maintenance, and rehabilitation of farm-to-market roads, bridges, post-harvest facilities, public markets, and common service facilities such as production and display centers, fish ports, etc;

c.        Agro-forestry community projects, such as Tree planting, seedling preparation, reforestation, etc; and

d.        Other relevant programs and projects.

SEC. 6. Application Process — Each applicants must submit the following to PESO-Manila:
•        Barangay Certificate;
•        Affidavit of No Income;
•        KASAMA Application Form issued by PESO-Manila with a 2x2 picture;
•        Government-issued ID.

SEC. 7. Benefits — All qualified beneficiaries shall receive payments corresponding to the tasks performed and the period of employment, as may be determined by PESO-Manila.

SEC. 8. Funding Source — The funds for the implementation of the KASAMA Program shall come from available funds of the City of Manila.

SEC. 9. Separability Clause — If any provision of this Ordinance or the application of such provision to other persons or circumstances is declared invalid, provisions thereof not afffected shall remain in full force and effect.

SEC. 10. Repealing Clause — All Memorandums, rules, regulations, and issuances inconsistent with this Ordinance are hereby repealed, modified, or amended accordingly.

SEC. 11. Effectivity Clause — This Ordinance shall take effect immediately upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on January 13, 2022.

ORDINANCE NO. 8797

AN ORDINANCE GRANTING FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE TO JOB ORDER
WORKERS, CONTRACT OF SERVICE OR OTHER SIMILAR SCHEMES OF THE CITY
GOVERNMENT OF MANILA AND PROVIDING FUNDS THEREFOR IN THE TOTAL
AMOUNT OF FIFTY-ONE MILLION ONE HUNDRED FIFTY THOUSAND PESOS
(PHP. 51,150,000.00), AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, on 8 March 2020, Presidential Proclamation No. 922, s. 2020, was issued declaring a State of Public Health Emergency throughout the Philippines due to the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19);

WHEREAS, Proclamation No. 929, s. 2020, was promulgated on 16 March 2020 declaring a State of Calamity for a period of six (6) months due to COVID-19. The state of calamity was later extended for a period of one (1) year from 13 September 2020 to 12 September 2021 by virtue of Proclamation No. 1021, s. 2020, promulgated on 16 September 2020;

WHEREAS, Proclamation No. 1218, s. 2021, promulgated on 10 September 2021, further extended the period of a State of Calamity throughout the country for a period of one (1) year effective 13 September 2021 to 12 September 2022, unless earlier lifted or extended as circumstances may warrant;

WHEREAS, said Presidential Proclamations enjoined all government agencies and Local Government Units (LGUs) to render full assistance to and cooperation with each other and mobilize the necessary resources to undertake critical, urgent and appropriate disaster response, aid and measures in a timely manner to curtail and eliminate the threat of COVID-19;

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code of 1991 states that: “Every local government unit shall exercise the powers expressly granted, those necessarily implied therefrom, as well as powers necessary, appropriate or incidental for its efficient and effective governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare. Within their respective territorial jurisdictions, local government units shall ensure and support, among other things, the preservation and enrichment of culture, promote health and safety, enhance the right of the people to a balanced ecology, encourage and support the development of appropriate and self-reliant scientific and technological capabilities, improve public morals, enhance economic prosperity and social justice, promote full employment among their residents, maintain peace and order, and preserve the comfort and convenience of their inhabitants” (Section 16 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, job orders, contract of service and personnel under other similar schemes of the City Government of Manila, who perform significant roles in the implementation of the City’s programs, projects and activities, are in need of financial assistance due to the detrimental economic effects brought about by the COVID-19 pandemic to all Filipino families;

WHEREAS, the same Code provides that all budgetary proposals shall be included and considered in the budget preparation process. After the local chief executive concerned shall have submitted the executive budget to the sanggunian, no ordinance providing for a supplemental budget shall be enacted, except when supported by funds actually available as certified by the local treasurer or by new revenue sources (Section 321 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, Section 336 of the Local Government Code states that funds shall be available exclusively for the specific purpose for which they have been appropriated. No ordinance shall be passed authorizing the transfer of appropriations from one item to another. However, the local chief executive or the presiding officer of the sangguniang concerned may, by ordinance, be authorized to augment any item in the approved annual budget for their respective offices from savings in other items within the same expense class of their respective appropriations;

WHEREAS, the local legislative body approved Resolution No. 24, adopted by the Executive Committee of the City Development Council on December 13, 2021, entitled: “A RESOLUTION APPROVING THE AMENDMENT OF THE ANNUAL INVESTMENT PROGRAM AND THE ISSUANCE OF A SUPPLEMENTAL INVESTMENT PROGRAM FOR FY 2021 FOR THE GRANT OF FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE TO JOB ORDER WORKERS, CONTRACT OF SERVICE OR OTHER SIMILAR SCHEMES OF THE CITY GOVERNMENT OF MANILA”: NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:
SECTION 1. Financial Assistance. — The Financial Assistance of Five Thousand Pesos (PhP. 5,000.00) each shall be granted to Job Order Workers, Contract of Service Workers, or those under other similar schemes of the City Government of Manila to help ease the financial burden brought about by the economic downturn due to the COVID-19 crisis.

SEC. 2. Augmentation and Fund Sources. — The Special Activities Fund-Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (SAF-MOOE) Account shall be augmented in the total amount of Fifty-One Million One Hundred Fifty Thousand Pesos (PhP. 51,150,000.00) from savings from various MOOE Accounts under the FY 2021 Executive Budget for the grant of the said financial assistance.

Attached are the following details:
Annex A — Declaration of Savings under MOOE for Augmentation of Funds;
Annex B — Budgetary Requirement for Financial Assistance.

SEC. 3. Separability Clause. — If any provision of this Ordinance is declared invalid or unconstitutional, the other provisions not affected thereby shall remain valid and subsisting.

SEC. 4. Effectivity Clause. — This Ordinance shall take effect immediately upon its approval.

On the motion presented by the Hon. Joel R. Chua, which was duly seconded by all those present, this Ordinance was finally approved for third and final reading by the City Council of Manila on December 20, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8795

AN ORDINANCE AUTHORIZING THE GRANT OF THE PRODUCTIVITY ENHANCEMENT INCENTIVE OF THE EMPLOYEES OF THE CITY GOVERNMENT OF
MANILA AND PROVIDING FUNDS THEREFOR FROM PERSONAL SERVICES SAVINGS AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, Executive Order No. (E.O.) 201, s. 2016, entitled: "Modifying the Salary Schedule for Civilian Government Personnel and Authorizing the Grant of Additional Benefits for both Civilian and Military and Uniformed Personnel", mandates the grant of Productivity Enhancement Incentives (PEI) to national and local government employees;

WHEREAS, as provided by E.O. 201, the PEI is meant to improve the productivity of government workers. It is granted to government workers, alongside the upward adjustment of the salary schedule in the bureaucracy;

WHEREAS, Budget Circular No. 2017-4, issued by the Department of Budget and Management (DBM), outlines the guidelines on the grant of PEI to government personnel;

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code of 1991 states that: “Every local government unit shall exercise the powers expressly granted, those necessarily implied therefrom, as well as powers necessary, appropriate, or incidental for its efficient and effective governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare. Within their respective territorial jurisdictions, local government units shall ensure and support, among other things, the preservation and enrichment of culture, promote health and safety, enhance the right of the people to a balanced ecology, encourage and support the development of appropriate and self-reliant scientific and technological capabilities, improve public morals, enhance economic prosperity and social justice, promote full employment among their residents, maintain peace and order, and preserve the comfort and convenience of their inhabitants” (Section 16 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, the same Code provides that all budgetary proposals shall be included and considered in the budget preparation process. After the local chief executive concerned shall have submitted the executive budget to the sanggunian, no ordinance providing for a supplemental budget shall be enacted, except when supported by funds actually available as certified by the local treasurer or by new revenue sources (Section 321 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, Section 336 of the Local Government Code states that funds shall be available exclusively for the specific purpose for which they have been appropriated. No ordinance shall be passed authorizing any transfer of appropriations from one item to another. However, the local chief executive or the presiding officer of the sanggunian concerned may, by ordinance, be authorized to augment any item in the approved annual budget for their respective offices from savings in other items within the same expense class of their respective appropriations;

WHEREAS, earlier today, the local legislative body approved Resolution No. 22, Series of 2021, adopted by the Executive Committee of the City Development Council, entitled: “A RESOLUTION APPROVING THE AMENDMENT OF THE ANNUAL INVESTMENT PROGRAM AND THE ISSUANCE OF A SUPPLEMENTAL INVESTMENT PROGRAM FOR FY 2021 FOR THE GRANT OF THE PRODUCTIVITY ENHANCEMENT INCENTIVE OF THE CITY GOVERNMENT EMPLOYEES OF THE CITY OF MANILA”: NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it Ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:
SECTION 1. Productivity Enhancement Incentive (PEI). — The PEI shall be granted to the regular, casual, and contractual employees of the City Government of Manila for Fiscal Year 2021, pursuant to DBM Budget Circular No. 2017-4 dated December 4, 2017. The Special Activities Fund–Personal Services (SAF-PS) shall be augmented for the grant of PEI in the total amount of Forty-Five Million Seven Hundred Fifty Thousand Pesos (PhP. 45,750,000.00).

SEC. 2. Source of Funds. — The funds to augment the SAF-PS for the grant of PEI shall be sourced from PS savings in the total amount of Forty-Five Million Seven Hundred Fifty Thousand Pesos (PhP. 45,750,000.00).

SEC. 3. Effectivity Clause. — This Ordinance shall take effect upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on December 13, 2021.

fines:
Violation by an Individual Person. —  Any person who violates any provision of this Code shall be punished as follows:
a) For the First Offense – a fine of not more than Three Thousand Pesos (PhP 3,000.00);
b) For the Second Offense – a fine of not more than Five Thousand Pesos (PhP 5,000.00) and the revocation of the Health Certificate.
SEC. 86. Violation by an Establishment. —  Any establishment that violates any provision of this Code shall be punished as follows:
