ORDINANCE NO. 8773

AN ORDINANCE GRANTING A GENERAL AMNESTY ON SURCHARGES, PENALTIES AND INTERESTS INCURRED DUE TO DELINQUENT BUSINESS TAXES, REAL PROPERTY TAXES, REGULATORY FEES, AND OTHER SERVICE CHARGES

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, the current pandemic has brought about unexpected socio-economic challenges to the country. As a result, many businesses have remained closed further causing the loss of jobs and opportunities. Amidst the health and safety challenges is the struggle to keep one's livelihood afloat;

WHEREAS, this situation makes it difficult for taxpayers to settle their obligations with the city. As a consequence, these unpaid impositions have incurred surcharge and penalty interests;

WHEREAS, in response to the plight of his constituents, the Honorable City Mayor, Francisco “Isko Moreno” Domagoso, submitted a letter to the City Council requesting for the enactment of an ordinance granting a general amnesty on all delinquent business taxes, real property taxes, regulatory fees, and other service charges;

WHEREAS, in the aforesaid letter, the City Mayor cited a report duly submitted by the City Treasurer stating that as of August 2021, the city has already realized 62.88% of its target collections for the fiscal year;

WHEREAS, the proposed general amnesty will, to a certain extent, cushion the socio-economic impact brought about by the pandemic and greatly help local businesses and property owners to recover from their losses;

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code (Sections 168, 169 and 255, R.A. No. 7160) authorizes the City Government of Manila to impose surcharge and penalty interests on certain unpaid taxes, fees and charges;

WHEREAS, Section 192 of the said law likewise authorizes the City Government, through an ordinance, to grant tax exemptions, incentives or reliefs under such terms and conditions as it may deem necessary: NOW, THEREFORE,
Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. Scope. — The General Amnesty shall apply on all appropriate surcharges, penalties and interests incurred due to unpaid local business taxes, regulatory fees and service charges; interest penalties on all classes of delinquent real properties (Residential, Commercial, Industrial and Special) within the territorial jurisdiction of the City of Manila; and penalties on all other overdue accounts. The Amnesty may be availed from OCTOBER 1, 2021 until DECEMBER 29, 2021 only.
SEC. 2. Who May Avail. — The Tax Amnesty shall be granted to taxpayers or individuals who:
a. Own, operate or are engaged in any business enterprise within the City of Manila which has a delinquent account or unpaid business tax, regulatory fee or other service charges to be paid to the City Government;
b. Own or administer real property declared for the first time subject to back taxes. The property shall be assessed based on the prevailing Fair Market Values and Assessment Levels under Ordinance No. 8330;
c. Own or administer any delinquent real property [Land, Building or ‘es Machinery] with or without Notices of Collection;
d. Violated traffic and parking rules imposed under the Manila Traffic Code (Ordinance No. 8092, as amended) and the No Contact Apprehension Program (Ordinance No. 8676). Provided, that those who have incurred two or more violations shall need to pay only the penalty for the first violation. Provided finally, that fees incurred from the succeeding violations including penalties thereof shall thereby be waived;
e. Have pending local tax cases before any judicial, quasi-judicial, or administrative body concerning local business taxes, fees, and charges or real property taxes imposed and assessed by the City of Manila. Provided that these cases have not attained finality of judgment upon effectivity of this Ordinance. Provided further, that Compromise Agreements must be executed between the parties on or before December 29, 2021; and
f. Have any transaction to secure a license, permit or any and all other services with the City Government of Manila.

SEC. 3. Waiver of Surcharge and Interest Penalties. — All corresponding accrued surcharge and interest penalties which any delinquent tax, regulatory fee or service charge may have incurred shall be deemed waived upon full payment of the principal amount of the basic tax, fee or charge within the period of effectivity of this Code.

SEC. 4. Application of Payments. — All taxes paid under this Ordinance shall first be applied to prior years’ tax delinquencies until all the tax deficiencies shall have been paid in full.

In the event that a taxpayer is unable to fully pay and settle the subsisting business or real property tax delinquencies within the effectivity of this Ordinance, the payments made pursuant to and by virtue hereof shall be deducted from the principal amount of delinquent tax and the outstanding surcharge and penalty interest, when applicable, shall again be imposed thereon and be due and demandable.

For taxpayers who have partially paid their taxes before the implementation of this Ordinance through compromise agreements, installment, or staggered payment methods, they may opt to pay the remaining balance in full during the effectivity of this Ordinance. The remaining surcharges and penalty interests accrued thereof shall then be waived.

SEC. 5. Implementing Rules and Regulations. — The Office of the City Treasurer is hereby directed to issue within five (5) days upon the approval of this Ordinance the necessary rules and regulations including other administrative guidelines for the implementation of the same.

SEC. 6. Information Dissemination. — An intensified and widespread information dissemination program shall be implemented to encourage taxpayers, including those residing outside the City of Manila, to avail the benefits of this Ordinance.

The Secretary to the City Council is hereby directed to publish a notice of a gist of this Ordinance in any newspaper of general circulation once every week throughout its effectivity. Likewise, the Manila Public Information Office is hereby directed to coordinate with national news agencies to inform the general public of this Ordinance.

Further, the Manila Barangay Bureau shall issue a memorandum instructing all Barangays to inform their constituents regarding this measure. And, finally, as mentioned under Section 2(d) hereof, the City Legal Office shall inform taxpayers with pending tax cases of their option to enter into a compromise agreement and settle their obligations through this Ordinance.

SEC. 7. Repealing Clause. — All ordinances or portions thereof which are contrary to the provisions of this Ordinance are hereby deemed repealed or modified accordingly.

SEC. 8. Separability Clause. — If any part, section or provision of this Ordinance shall be held invalid or unconstitutional by a competent court, other parts or portions that are not affected thereby shall remain valid.

SEC. 9. Effectivity Clause. — This Ordinance shall be effective from October 1, 2021 until December 29, 2021 only.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on September 20, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8750

AN ORDINANCE FURTHERMORE AMENDING THE PROVISIONS OF
ORDINANCE NO. 7885, AS AMENDED BY ORDINANCE NOS. 8120 AND 8635,
ENTITLED: "AN ORDINANCE AUTHORIZING THE CITY GOVERNMENT OF MANILA
TO OPERATE THE DALUBHASAAN NG MAYNILA (CITY COLLEGE OF MANILA) AND
FOR SUCH OTHER PURPOSES", ENACTED ON APRIL 17, 1995, PURSUANT TO THE
REQUIREMENTS OF THE COMMISSION ON HIGHER EDUCATION (CHED) FOR
HIGHER EDUCATION INSTITUTIONS (HEIS), PROVIDING FUNDS THEREFOR, AND
FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE

WHEREAS, Universidad de Manila (UDM) has come a long way as an educational institution since it was established by the City Government of Manila back in 1995 as the then City College of Manila (CCM);

WHEREAS, the current administration of the City of Manila, led by Mayor Francisco "Isko Moreno" Domagoso, who is also the ex-officio Chairman of the Board of Regents of UDM, seeks the Commission on Higher Education's (CHED) recognition of UDM as a Higher Education Institution or HEI;

WHEREAS, should UDM obtain HEI status upon due recognition and conferment by CHED, UDM will then be a rightful recipient of various substantial subsidies and/or funding from the National Government that will surely boost UDM's institutional capabilities to provide accessible, free and quality education to the youth of the City of Manila;

WHEREAS, in order for UDM to successfully obtain CHED's "institutional recognition" as an HEI, UDM needs to comply with CHED's requirements as stated under CHED Memorandum Order (CMO) No. 32, Series of 2006 and CMO No. 42, Series of 2016, both CMOs being the bases of CHED's "Validation Tool" entitled: "Compliance to Requirements for Recognition as Higher Education Institution/Certificate of Authority to establish a Higher Education Institution";

WHEREAS, pursuant to CMO No. 32, Series of 2006 and CMO No. 42, Series of 2016, the "Ordinance establishing a local Higher Education Institution," which is Ordinance No. 7885, as amended by Ordinance No. 8120 and Ordinance No. 8635, in the case of UDM, MUST further INCLUDE provisions for the following:

a. Membership of the Governing Board consistent with those provided under CMO No. 32, Series of 2006, and CMO No. 4, Series of 2016;
b. Search Committee for the President of the University;
c. Qualifications of the President of the University;
d. Continuing appropriation and financial support of the Local Government Unit creating the HEI;
e. Local Government Unit allotting and/or allotting a real property registered in its name for the exclusive use of the HEI; and
f. Local Government Unit approving and considering the Project Development Plan and Institutional Development Plan of the HEI in crafting the Local Government Unit's budget and its own corresponding "plans", among others.

WHEREAS, the above-enumerated proposed amendments to Ordinance No. 7885, as amended by Ordinance No. 8120 and Ordinance No. 8635, will bring a huge impact for the betterment of the quality of free education for the youth of the City of Manila for the years and generations to come: NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. Declaration of Policy. - It shall hereby be declared the policy of the City of Manila to be genuinely committed, in consonance with the policy of the State, in promoting the right of all citizens to quality education at all levels and to make such education accessible to all. Moreover, the City of Manila, aware of its obligations to give the poor but talented and gifted students of the City of Manila the opportunity to develop their potentials, is committed to establish another tertiary school to accommodate the graduates of secondary public schools to pursue college education.

The Board shall be composed of the eleven (11) members as follows:   

Chairman - City Mayor 
Vice Chairman - University President 

Nine (9) members of the Board: 
(a) Chairman of the Committee on Education of the City Council (ex-officio) 
(b) Superintendent of City Schools (ex-officio) 
(c) President of the Faculty Association 
(d) President of the Supreme Student Government 
(e) President of the Alumni Association 
(f) Two (2) representatives from accredited Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs), preferably from business or industry sectors 
(g) Representative from the Association of Local Colleges and Universities (ALCU) 
(h) Representative from the Department of Science and Technology (DOST)    

All members of the Board, with the exception of the Chairman and the two (2) ex-officio members, shall be appointed by the Mayor of the City of Manila with the consent of the City Council. 

The appointment of the representative from the ALCU shall be subject to the confirmation of the President of the national ALCU. The appointment of the representative from the DOST, who shall hold rank not lower than director, shall be subject to the confirmation of the DOST Secretary.   

All appointive members of the Board shall serve a term of six (6) years, or until their successors shall have been appointed and qualified; PROVIDED, however, that the representatives from the Faculty, Alumni Association, and the Supreme Student Government be co-terminus with their respective tenure of office.   

The Regional Director of the Commission on Higher Education (CHED), or his/her duly designated representative may be invited as a resource person during board meetings.   

SEC. 6. Requirements and Allowances of the Members of the Board. - All members of the Board shall be citizens of the Philippines. They shall serve without compensation other than the reasonable allowance for attendance in Board meetings and for official business duly authorized by the Board.   

SEC. 7. Vacancy. - In case of vacancy in the Board by reason of resignation, death, or other forms of incapacity of any member of the Board, such vacancy shall be filled by appointment of the Mayor: PROVIDED, that, the appointee shall serve only for the unexpired portion of the vacated term.   

SEC. 8. Conflict of Interest. - Members of the Board shall not have any business interest, directly or indirectly, in any aspect of University operations.   

SEC. 9. General Powers of the Board of Regents. - The University shall have the general powers set out under Section 35 of Republic Act No. 11232, otherwise known as the Revised Corporation Code of the Philippines, all other applicable powers of corporations under Title IV of said Code, and such other functions as are necessary to carry out the purposes of the corporation and administration of the said university, and the exercise of its corporate powers are hereby vested exclusively in the Board of Regents and the President of the University insofar as authorized by the Board.

SEC. 10. Powers and Duties of the Board of Regents. - The Board of Regents shall have the following powers and duties, in consonance with existing laws and in addition to its general powers under Section 9 hereof:   

1. To establish policies, guidelines and procedures for participative decision-making;   

2. To develop academic arrangements and linkage for institutional capability building with appropriate Institutions and agencies, both public and private, local and foreign;   

3. To institutionalize research and extension programs;   

4. To receive and appropriate such sums of money, properties, or materials as may be provided by Ordinance of the City of Manila for the support of the University;  

5. To provide for the establishment of undergraduate and graduate schools, specifically in, but not limited to, Science and Technology, considering the priorities of the City and national needs;   

6. To approve the courses of study and rules of discipline recommended by the University Council as hereafter provided for, and to fix tuition and other fees; 
  
7. To determine/approve curricular programs and course offerings in response to the needs and demands of the community provided that these should comply with the provisions of CMO No. 10, S. 2005;   

8. To promulgate policies on admission, retention and graduation of students;  

9. To confer degrees for which graduating students are qualified, and honorary degrees and titles upon persons in recognition of their wisdom, statesmanship, or service in government and to society, as well as in due regard to eminence in philosophy, science, technology, literature, and community service;   

10. To provide fellowships and scholarships for students, faculty and staff on the basis of merit;  

11. To establish professional chairs in the University's colleges and to provide or arrange for the maintenance or endowment of such chairs;   

12. To provide for academic ranks and approve the appointment for teaching personnel and to fix the compensation commensurate with such ranks;   

13. To receive from the City of Manila assistance to augment the internal sources of funds, as may be provided, for the support of the University in the manner it may determine, and its discretion, to carry out the purposes and functions on the University. Such fees and charges, including government subsidiaries and other income generated by the University, shall constitute its regular fund and shall be deposited in any authorized government depository bank, and all interests that shall accrue therefore shall form part of the same fund for the use of the University. If, for reason of control, the University shall be able to pursue any project for which funds have been appropriated and allocated under its approved program of expenditures, the Board, may authorize the use of said funds for any reasonable purpose which, in its discretion, may be necessary and urgent for the attainment of objectives and goals of the University;   

14. To provide a reasonable system of compensation and fringe benefits such as housing, medical, and health insurances, scholarships for direct descendants of University personnel, legal support in case of litigation and other benefits as may be allowed by the Salary Standardization Law and other compensation laws. Such compensation benefits shall be for all University officials, faculty, and staff, full time or part time, as applicable. Non-pecuniary benefits shall be in accordance with rules and regulations on hours of service, and such other conditions as the Board may deem proper;  

15. To receive in trust, tax free, all legacies, gifts, donations, and grants of real and personal properties, and any other form of donation, and to administer the same for the benefit of the University or any part thereof in accordance with the instructions of the donor, or in default thereof, in such manner as it may determine;   

16. To disburse the appropriated funds in accordance with the line item expenditure of the University as determined by the Board, subject to limitations imposed by law: PROVIDED, that any or all funds allocated and accruing to the University shall be put and kept under its name and account and PROVIDED FURTHER, that any surplus for unappropriated amount at the end of each year shall remain with the coffers and considered as savings of the University as may be allowed by the Local Government Code and other budgeting laws. 
Likewise, there shall be a budget allocation for the accreditation of programs to be provided by the City of Manila. The form, content, manner, procedure in approving appropriations for the University shall strictly follow the procedure for approving appropriations for other departments and offices of the City of Manila, including but not limited to, presentation of proper documentation, justification, and accomplishment reports as required by the Local Government Code and other budgetary laws;   

17. To prescribe rules of its own governance, to establish the governance structure of the University, and to enact for the governance of the University such general policies and regulations as are consistent with the purposes of the University as defined in Section 3 of this Ordinance; 
  
18. To promulgate rules and regulations of discipline governing University officials, faculty, and staff members, including removal from the service for cause, after due process;   

19. To ensure the efficient management of non-academic services such as medical and dental, guidance and counseling, canteen, buildings, grounds, property maintenance and similar services;   

20. To appoint the President of the University upon recommendation of the Search Committee;   

21. To confirm appointments of other school officials, teaching and non-teaching personnel, appointed by the President of the University;   

22. To delegate any of its powers and duties provided herein to the President of the University and/or other officials of the University as it may deem appropriate so as to expedite the administration of the affairs of the University;   

23. To invite representatives from other government or private entities as resource person(s) of the Board;  

24. In coordination with the City Council of Manila, to provide for the regular support for the development, operation and maintenance of the University;  

25. To recommend to the City Council of Manila policies on tertiary education and other related development legislation on effective governance and management; and   

26. To exercise such other powers and duties not inconsistent with laws as may be necessary or essential to carry out its purposes.   

The Board of Regents shall promulgate policies in accordance with the declared state policies on higher education, as well as the policies, standards and thrusts of the CHED under Republic Act No. 7722 and other pertinent laws.   

SEC. 11. Processes. - Actions and processes against the Board of Regents shall be served on the University President or the Board Secretary thereof.   

SEC. 12. Meetings of the Board of Regents. - The Board of Regents shall hold its regular meetings at least once a month, or in special meetings as may be deemed necessary by the Chairman and the University President. A majority of the members shall constitute a quorum to transact business. The University President shall determine and prepare the agenda of all meetings of the Board. All acts of the Board shall be collegial, and no member may take action on any matter on his/her own. At the end of each fiscal year, the Board shall submit an annual report to the Mayor and the City Council.   

SEC. 13. Administration of the University. The responsibility of University administration shall devolve upon the University President and its officials.   

SEC. 14. University Council. - There shall be a University Council, consisting of the President of the University and all members of the faculty of the University holding the rank of professor, associate professor and assistant professor. Subject to existing laws, the Council shall have the power to prescribe the course of study and rules of discipline, provided those matters are first approved by the Board of Regents. Subject to the same limitations, it shall fix the requirements for admission to any college of the University, as well as for graduation and the conferment of degrees. The Council alone shall have the power to recommend students or other to be recipients of degrees. Through its President or committees, it shall have disciplinary powers over the students within the limits prescribed by the rules of discipline approved by the Board of Regents.   

SEC. 15. University President. - The President of the University, who is the Chief Academic and Executive Officer of the University, shall be appointed by the Board of Regents, upon the recommendation of a duly constituted Search Committee, for a term of six (6) years, subject to reappointment, unless sooner removed for cause, such as, incapacity, incompetence, dishonesty and/or final conviction of a crime involving moral turpitude and other grave offenses as decided upon a competent court of law. The President of the University shall hold an appropriate earned doctoral degree with at least five (5) years of relevant administrative experience. The President of the University shall receive salary, emoluments and fringe benefits commensurate with his/her position and qualification as determined by the Board as may be allowed by law. The powers and duties of the President of the University, in addition to this specifically provided for in this Ordinance, shall be those pertaining to the Office of the President of the University.   

SEC. 16. Search Committee for the University President. - The Search Committee for the President of the University shall have five (5) members to be appointed by the Board of Regents, with members each representing the academe, Civil Service Commission (CSC), CHED, ALCU and an accredited NGO preferably from business or industry sector. Said members shall elect amongst them a Chairman and a Vice Chairman, six (6) months before the expiration of the term of office of the incumbent President of the University.   

SEC. 17. Other University Officials, Academic and Non-Academic Personnel. - The Executive Vice President, Vice President, deans, directors, registrars, administrative officers, accountants, faculty and non-teaching personnel shall be appointed by the President of the University, subject to the confirmation of the Board of Regents. Provided that the Vice President for Academic Affairs must be a holder of an earned doctoral degree; provided, further, that their appointments shall be pursuant to existing civil service laws, rules, and regulations. In the appointment of professors, instructors, and other personnel of the University, no religious tests shall be required, nor shall the religious opinions or affiliations be made a matter of examination or inquiry.   

SEC. 18. Structure and Organization. - The President shall recommend to the Board for approval, the structure and organization of the University which shall define efficiently and effectively its operations for the achievement of its goals and objectives.   

SEC. 19. Board Secretary and University Legal Counsel. - The Board of Regents shall appoint a Board Secretary, upon the recommendation of the University President, who shall be responsible for the documentation of the minutes of the board meetings, board resolutions and any other duties and/or functions to be assigned by the Board pertaining to the affairs, duties and functions of the latter. There shall be a separate University Legal Counsel to be appointed by the University President, subject to the confirmation of the Board, who shall handle all legal matters concerning all facets of university affairs.   

SEC. 20. Board of Visitors. - The Mayor, the Vice Mayor, and the Members of the City Council shall constitute the Board of Visitors of the University. As Chairman of the Board of Visitors, the Mayor shall convene the Board in order to discharge its duties, such as attendance in graduation ceremonies, making visits at the University, as it may deem necessary and other visitorial duties and privileges as may be provided by law.   

SEC. 21. Assured Continuous Appropriation and Financial Support for the University. - The City Council shall appropriate funds for the operations of the University, the regular Annual appropriations of which shall be included in the Executive Budget of the Office of the City Mayor as lump sum appropriation or such amount thereof to support and sustain the full operation and maintenance of the University; PROVIDED, that the City Council may appropriate additional funds for special programs and/or projects which may be deemed necessary to be undertaken by the University, outside of its regular annual appropriation subject to the presentation of proper documentation, justification and accomplishment reports as required by the Local Government Code and other budgetary laws.   

SEC. 22. Allocation of City Owned Real Property as Site for the University. - The City of Manila shall allocate a real property, through a usufruct agreement between the City and the University, with appropriate size and location pursuant to the applicable provisions of the Building Code of the Philippines, as the school site of the University.   

SEC. 23. Project and Institutional Plans of the University. - Any and all project and/or institutional plans of the University, as approved by the Board of Regents, shall be submitted to and approved by the City Council to ensure that said plans of the University shall be incorporated and/or integrated into the formulation of the corresponding plans and budget of the City Government of Manila.   

SEC. 24. Emblem, Color and Seal. - The University shall adopt its emblem, color, seal and other appurtenances consistent with the reflective of the Philippine culture and values that shall enhance the uniqueness and dignity of the Filipino identity.   

SEC. 25. Progress Report. - The Board of Regents, shall file with the CHED, the Mayor, and the City Council an annual detailed report, setting forth the progress, condition, and needs of the University.   

SEC. 26. Reportorial Requirements and Auditing of Accounts. - The University shall submit an annual report to the Mayor, through the Local Finance Committee and the City Council containing the financial statements, statements of assets and liabilities, actual projected income from tuition fees and other revenue sources, contracts and investments entered into, including programs of expenditures, accomplished reports on the utilization of funds from the City and other sources, and other necessary reports. All accounts and disbursements of the University shall be audited by the Commission on Audit.   

SEC. 27. Oversight Committee and Sunset Review. - An Oversight Committee composed of the Mayor, the Vice Mayor, the President of the University and their designated representatives shall constitute the oversight committee to oversee the transition in terms of setting up the University's procurement, payroll, and revenue collection systems and such other systems and processes that are critical of the University's operation. It shall likewise conduct a review on the grant of fiscal autonomy to the University upon the lapse of five (5) years from the approval hereof.   

SEC. 28. Transitory Provisions. - Upon signing of this Ordinance by the Mayor, the University shall submit, in thirty (30) days, its enhanced organizational chart and operations manual to the Mayor. The Local Finance Committee shall transfer the necessary fund of the University for the current fiscal year subject to the submission of pertinent documentation and justification as required by the Local Government Code and other budgetary laws.   

SEC. 29. Rules of Construction. - No statutory or other issuances shall diminish the powers, rights, privileges and benefits accorded to the University under this Ordinance or enjoyed at present by it under other issuances not otherwise modified or repealed under this Ordinance, unless subsequent legislation expressly provides for their repeal, amendment, or modification. Any case of doubt in the interpretation of any of the provisions of this Charter shall be resolved in favor of the academic freedom and fiscal autonomy of the University.   

SEC. 30. Appropriations. - The amount needed to carry out the implementation of this Ordinance shall be charged against the lump sum appropriation of the current fiscal year and other internal funds of the University. Thereafter, such lump sum representing the responsibility of the City of Manila for the continued growth, operation, maintenance, and requirements for the Commission on Higher Education (CHED) Accreditation. The University may use unexpended balances in any appropriation for purposes that the Board determines.   

SEC. 31. Separability Clause. Should any provision herein be declared unconstitutional, the same shall not affect the validity of the other provisions of this Act.   

SEC. 32. Repealing Clause. - Ordinance No. 7885, as amended, and all laws, decrees, orders, rules, and regulations or other issuances or parts inconsistent with the provisions of this Ordinance are hereby repealed or modified accordingly. This Ordinance can only be repealed by a UNANIMOUS VOTE of all members of the City Council.   

SEC. 33. Effectivity Clause. - This Ordinance shall take effect upon its approval.   

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on May 24, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8740

AN ORDINANCE PROHIBITING ANY PERSON, INSTITUTION, CORPORATION, GROUP, OR ORGANIZATION WHO SHALL ENGAGE IN THE SALE, DISTRIBUTION, OR ADMINISTRATION OF COVID-19 VACCINES FOR GAIN, INCOME, OR PROFIT, WHILE THE COUNTRY IS IN A STATE OF PUBLIC HEALTH EMERGENCY AND WITHOUT FULL MARKET AUTHORIZATION ISSUED BY THE FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION, AND PROVIDING PENALTIES THEREFOR

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, on March 9, 2020, President Rodrigo Roa Duterte issued Proclamation No. 922, declaring the country under a State of Public Health Emergency;
WHEREAS, a year later, or as of March 27, 2021, it was announced by the Inter-Agency Task Force for the Management of Emerging Infectious Diseases (IATF) that the Greater Manila Area, including Bulacan, Cavite, Laguna, and Rizal, would be placed under Enhanced Community Quarantine due to the continuous increase in reported COVID-19 cases starting from March 20 to April 04, 2021, and then again extended until April 11, 2021;
WHEREAS, as of April 5, 2021, the Philippines has 803,398 reported COVID-19 cases, 45,054 confirmed cases of which are from the City of Manila, as reported by the Department of Health;
WHEREAS, as of April 04, 2021, 43,603 total individuals have been vaccinated in the City of Manila out of a total population of 1.9 million residents;
WHEREAS, according to vaccine czar, Carlito Galvez, Jr., the delivery of vaccine doses from the World Health Organization would be slightly delayed due to “global logistics constraints” and that most manufacturing countries are restricting exports of the vaccines;
WHEREAS, under Sec. 5 of Republic Act No. 115251, private entities may procure COVID-19 vaccines only in cooperation with the Department of Health (DOH) and the National Task Force through a multi-party agreement, which shall include the DOH and the relevant supplier of COVID-19 vaccines;
WHEREAS, under Sec. 11 of R.A. No. 115251, “Beginning January 1, 2021, the procurement, importation, donation, storage, transport, deployment, and administration of COVID-19 vaccines...by private entities shall be exempt from customs duties, value-added tax, excise tax, donor's tax, and other fees: Provided, That the vaccines shall not be intended for resale or other commercial use and shall be distributed without consideration from persons to be vaccinated”;
WHEREAS, at present, the sale and/or purchase of vaccines from private persons or entities are prohibited under the law until a full market authorization is issued by the Philippine FDA. COVID-19 vaccine suppliers have only been given an Emergency Use Authorization (EUA) by the Philippine Government since the vaccines are unregistered (under development) during public health emergencies of international concern. It aims to expedite the availability of the drug to people affected by the public health emergency based on an essential set of available quality, safety, and efficacy performance data;
WHEREAS, Section 16 of R.A. 7160, otherwise known as the Local Government Code of 1991, provides the police power of the City to implement measures necessary for the protection of its citizens, which particularly states:
“SECTION 16. General Welfare. — Every local government unit shall exercise the powers expressly granted, those necessarily implied therefrom, as well as powers necessary, appropriate, or incidental for its efficient and effective governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare. Within their respective territorial jurisdictions, local government units shall ensure and support, among other things, the preservation and enrichment of culture, promote health and safety, enhance the right of the people to a balanced ecology, encourage and support the development of appropriate and self-reliant scientific and technological capabilities, improve public morals, enhance economic prosperity and social justice, promote full employment among their residents, maintain peace and order, and preserve the comfort and convenience of their inhabitants.”
WHEREAS, in conjunction with Sec. 11 of R.A. 115251 and in the exercise of the police power of the City of Manila, in order to discourage the manufacture, sale, and proliferation of fake COVID-19 vaccines for profit to the detriment of its citizenry, an ordinance penalizing these private entities from the commission of said acts is necessary: NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:
SECTION 1. It shall be unlawful for any person, institution, corporation, group, or organization to engage in the sale, distribution, or administration of COVID-19 vaccines for gain, income, or profit, while the country is in a state of public health emergency and without full market authorization issued by the Food and Drug Administration.

SEC. 2. Any person caught in violation of Section 1 hereof shall be fined Five Thousand Pesos (PhP. 5,000.00) and imprisonment not exceeding six (6) months.

If the violation is committed by a corporation or other juridical entity, the directors, officers, employees, or other officers thereof responsible for the violation shall be charged and penalized.
In addition thereto, the business license issued to the said persons, corporations, groups, or organizations shall be immediately revoked and they shall be banned from doing business in the City of Manila.

SEC. 3. If, for any reason or reasons, any part or provision of this Ordinance shall be held unconstitutional or invalid, other parts or provisions hereof, which are not affected thereby, shall continue to be in full force and effect.

SEC. 4. All ordinances, rules, or regulations in conflict with the provisions of this Ordinance are hereby repealed; PROVIDED, that the rights vested upon the effectivity of this Ordinance shall not be impaired.

SEC. 5. Effectivity Clause. — This Ordinance shall take effect immediately upon its approval and shall automatically be of no force and effect when the State of Public Health Emergency in the country is lifted.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on May 24, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8733

AN ORDINANCE RATIFYING THE DEED OF ABSOLUTE SALE ENTERED INTO BY THE CITY OF MANILA AND VANCOUVER LANDS, INC. FOR THE SUBJECT PATRIMONIAL PROPERTIES LOCATED AT 599 P. OCAMPO STREET, MALATE, MANILA, SPECIFICALLY A PORTION OF THE LOT COVERED BY TRANSFER CERTIFICATE OF TITLE NO. 002-2012004038, AND A PORTION OF THE LOT COVERED BY TRANSFER CERTIFICATE OF TITLE NO. 002-6571 OF THE REGISTRY OF DEEDS OF THE CITY OF MANILA

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, Vancouver Lands, Inc. is a corporation duly organized and existing under the laws of the Republic of the Philippines with its principal address at SIF Two E-Com Center, Harbor Drive, Mall of Asia Complex, Pasay City;
WHEREAS, the City Government of Manila is the absolute and registered owner of the parcel of land located at 599 P. Ocampo Street, Malate, Manila, specifically a portion of the lot covered by Transfer Certificate of Title No. 002-2012004038 and a portion of the lot covered by Transfer Certificate of Title No. 002-6571 of the Registry of Deeds of the City of Manila;
WHEREAS, on January 18, 2021, the City Council of Manila enacted Ordinance No. 8722 granting authority to the City Mayor, Honorable Francisco "Isko Moreno" Domagoso, to dispose of the above-described patrimonial properties of the City of Manila through public bidding and to subsequently sign all pertinent documents relative to the said disposal, including but not limited to the Contract of Sale, subject to all existing laws, rules, and regulations;
WHEREAS, on January 22 and 27, 2021, the Committee on Awards on Appraisal and Disposal of the City of Manila caused the publications of the Invitation to Submit Letter of Intent and to Bid for the public auction of the said property, and the Supplemental Bid Bulletin on February 5, 2021, in Tempo, a newspaper of general circulation. The Committee posted the same notices in three (3) conspicuous places at the premises of the Manila City Hall Building, setting the floor price of the project at One Hundred Seventy-Three Thousand Pesos (PhP 173,000.00) per square meter for the land and Ten Thousand Five Hundred Pesos (PhP 10,500.00) for the improvements, or a total of One Billion Three Hundred Fifty-Eight Million Two Hundred Eight Thousand Pesos (PhP 1,358,208,000.00), as recommended by the Asset Management Committee of the City of Manila;
WHEREAS, in response to the Public Notices, three (3) companies submitted their respective letters of intent, namely: SILANGANG DAGAT HOLDINGS CORPORATION, VANCOUVER LANDS, INC., and AM. ORETA & CO., INC. The representatives of SILANGANG DAGAT HOLDINGS CORPORATION and VANCOUVER LANDS, INC. attended the Pre-Bid Conference held on February 11, 2021, at 2:00 PM at the Conference Room of the Office of the Secretary to the Mayor, where VANCOUVER LANDS, INC. and AM. ORETA & CO., INC. passed the preliminary evaluation during the opening of bids on February 18, 2021;
WHEREAS, due to an expired Bank Certification, SILANGANG DAGAT HOLDINGS CORPORATION failed to pass the eligibility requirements, thereby returning to the said company their Second Envelope unopened containing their Financial Bid Proposal;
WHEREAS, during the opening of bids on February 18, 2021, the two (2) companies which passed the preliminary evaluation submitted their respective bids. VANCOUVER LANDS, INC. was declared the winning bidder, having submitted the highest bid in the amount of One Billion Three Hundred Eighty-Two Million Four Hundred Seventy-Two Thousand Pesos (PhP 1,382,472,000.00);
WHEREAS, on February 19, 2021, during the Post-Qualification, the technical and financial documents submitted by VANCOUVER LANDS, INC. were carefully evaluated and were found to be responsive and advantageous to the City;
WHEREAS, Resolution No. 8 dated February 22, 2021, was unanimously passed by the Committee on Awards on Appraisal and Disposal of the City of Manila, finding the bid of VANCOUVER LANDS, INC. to be qualified and responsive for the sale, and recommending the sale of the above-described property to the said company;
WHEREAS, both parties have agreed to the sale, transfer, and conveyance of the above-described properties on an “AS-IS-WHERE-IS” basis: NOW,THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:
SECTION 1. Ratification. — The Deed of Absolute Sale entered into by the City of Manila and Vancouver Lands, Inc. for the subject patrimonial properties located at 599 P. Ocampo Street, Malate, Manila, specifically a portion of the lot covered by Transfer Certificate of Title No. 002-2012004038, and a portion of the lot covered by Transfer Certificate of Title No. 002-6571 of the Registry of Deeds of the City of Manila, is hereby ratified. A copy of the Deed of Absolute Sale is hereby attached and marked as Annex “A” and made an integral part hereof.

SEC. 2. Effectivity Clause. — This Ordinance shall take effect upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on March 4, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8732
AN ORDINANCE EXEMPTING ALL COVID-19 VACCINE PRODUCTS TO BE PROCURED BY THE CITY GOVERNMENT OF MANILA FROM PAYMENT OF ALL TAXES, FEES, AND CHARGES IMPOSED BY THE CITY OF MANILA FOR A PERIOD OF ONE YEAR OR FROM FEBRUARY 22, 2021 UNTIL FEBRUARY 22, 2022

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, on March 8, 2020, a State of Public Health Emergency was declared throughout the Philippines due to Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19). As of February 19, 2021, the Department of Health had already recorded five hundred fifty-seven thousand fifty-eight (557,058) COVID-positive cases with over eleven thousand (11,000) deaths;

WHEREAS, in December 2020, several pharmaceutical companies successfully produced vaccines against COVID-19, which were then rolled out and used by various countries;

WHEREAS, in January 2021, the City Council of Manila enacted several ordinances appropriating Two Hundred Fifty Million Pesos (PhP 250,000,000.00) for the procurement of COVID-19 vaccines to be used in the City;

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code of 1991 states that “every local government unit shall exercise the powers expressly granted, those necessarily implied therefrom, as well as powers necessary, appropriate, or incidental for its efficient and effective governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare. Within their respective territorial jurisdictions, local government units shall ensure and support, among other things, the preservation and enrichment of culture, promote health and safety, enhance the right of the people to a balanced ecology, encourage and support the development of appropriate and self-reliant scientific and technological capabilities, improve public morals, enhance economic prosperity and social justice, promote full employment among their residents, maintain peace and order, and preserve the comfort and convenience of their inhabitants.” (Section 16 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, the same Code provides that “local government units may, through ordinances duly approved, grant tax exemptions, incentives or reliefs under such terms and conditions as they may deem necessary” (Section 192 of Republic Act No. 7160); NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:
SECTION 1. All COVID-19 vaccine products to be procured by the City Government of Manila are hereby exempted from payment of all taxes, fees, and charges levied by the City.

SEC. 2. Period. — The exemption shall be for a period of one year or from February 22, 2021, until February 22, 2022.

SEC. 3. Effectivity Clause. — This Ordinance shall take effect upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on February 22, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8729
AN ORDINANCE AUTHORIZING THE DEPUTATION OF ENVIRONMENTAL POLICE UNDER THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SERVICES (DPS), DEFINING THEIR DUTIES AND FUNCTIONS AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, on December 20, 2019, the Honorable City Mayor signed Executive Order No. 60, directing the intensification of the enforcement of environmental laws, such as the Sanitation Code, Water Code, and Ecological Solid Waste Management Act;

WHEREAS, there are other laws and ordinances for the protection of the environment that are not being fully enforced or implemented for one reason or another;

WHEREAS, the protection and preservation of the environment is one of the priority programs of the present administration under Honorable City Mayor Francisco “Isko Moreno” Domagoso;

WHEREAS, pursuant to the Local Government Code and R.A. 9003, otherwise known as the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000, the City Government deems it necessary to impose penal sanctions for the prohibited acts as herein prescribed: NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:
SECTION 1. — The Honorable Mayor is hereby authorized to deputize personnel, either permanent or job order category, under the Department of Public Services, which shall be distributed to all eight hundred ninety-six (896) barangays.

SEC. 2. Powers and Duties:
The Environmental Police shall have the following powers and duties:
a) Apprehend all violators of the different environmental laws and ordinances for the protection of the environment, such as but not limited to:
1.        Illegal dumping of solid waste along streets, alleys, riverbanks, and in any public places;
2.        Incineration or open burning of solid waste;
3.        Causing or permitting the collection of garbage not segregated and placed in approved containers;
4.        Illegal cutting, destroying, or injuring of planted growing trees, flowering plants, shrubs, or plants of scenic value along public coastal roads, plazas, parks, school premises, or in any other public ground;
5.        Dumping and discharging of garbage, refuse, sewer waste, debris, toxic waste, and other pollutants from vessels, factories, commercial and industrial establishments, residential houses, and other structures into the Manila Bay, the Pasig River, and other waterways and bodies of water within the territorial jurisdiction of the City of Manila;
6.        Disposal of garbage, debris, and other waste materials in rivers, creeks, canals, and waterways;
7.        Littering or leaving trash and other refuse in the gutter, sidewalks, streets, alleyways, and roads, and allowing or leaving pet animals to defecate or urinate outside their property line;
8.        Storing, dumping, or placing wastes, debris, junked or under-repair vehicles, dilapidated appliances, and other objects in any part of the road, street, or avenue or on any sidewalk which may impede or obstruct vehicular and pedestrian traffic;
9.        Disposal of effluent and sludge from motor repair shops, motor pools, bus and jeepney terminals, car wash, junk shop establishments, and battery shops into the drainage canals, creeks, rivers, or any body of water;
10.        Failure to provide segregated containers for biodegradable and non-biodegradable garbage for composting and recycling;
11.        Disposal of garbage, trash, rubbish, and refuse in open or unsealed containers; and
12.        All other prohibited acts prescribed under R.A. 9003 and the Clean Air Act, Clean Water Act, NIPAS Act, Wildlife Conservation Act, Mining Act, Forestry Code, and Face Mask Disposal Act.
If the offense is committed by a corporation, partnership, or other juridical entity duly organized in accordance with law, the Chief Executive Officer, President, General Manager, Managing Partner, or such other officer shall be liable for the commission of the offense penalized herein.
b) Educate people on the importance of protecting the environment and the proper way of waste segregation and disposal.

SEC. 3.  The Department of Public Services shall be mandated to conduct a periodic seminar, which shall include the participation of the Chief of Police or any representative, and shall administer written and oral examinations to all applicants for Environmental Police, subject to existing rules and regulations.

SEC. 4.  The City Solid Waste Management Board shall formulate the Implementing Rules and Regulations of this Ordinance within thirty (30) days after its approval, subject to the approval of the City Council. Such rules and regulations shall take effect fifteen (15) days after their publication.

SEC. 5.  All other regulations, issuances, ordinances, or parts thereof inconsistent with the provisions of this Ordinance are hereby repealed or modified accordingly.

SEC. 6. Effectivity Clause. — This Ordinance shall take effect upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on February 8, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8719
AN ORDINANCE RE-APPROPRIATING TWO HUNDRED MILLION PESOS (PHP. 200,000,000.00) AS SUPPLEMENTAL BUDGET NO. 1 FOR FISCAL YEAR 2021 TO COVER EXPENSES FOR COVID-19 VACCINES IN THE CITY OF MANILA


PREAMBLE

WHEREAS, on 8 March 2020, President Rodrigo Roa Duterte issued Presidential Proclamation No. 922, s. 2020, declaring a State of Public Health Emergency throughout the Philippines due to the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19). As of 2 January 2021, the Department of Health has already recorded 476,916 COVID-positive cases with almost 10,000 deaths. 26,842 of those positive cases were recorded in the City of Manila;

WHEREAS, in December 2020, several pharmaceutical companies successfully produced vaccines against COVID-19 which were then rolled out and used by various countries;

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code of 1991, states that: “Every local government unit shall exercise the powers expressly granted, those necessarily implied therefrom, as well as powers necessary, appropriate, or incidental for its efficient and effective governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare. Within their respective territorial jurisdictions, local government units shall ensure and support, among other things, the preservation and enrichment of culture, promote health and safety, enhance the right of the people to a balanced ecology, encourage and support the development of appropriate and self-reliant scientific and technological capabilities, improve public morals, enhance economic prosperity and social justice, promote full employment among their residents, maintain peace and order, and preserve the comfort and convenience of their inhabitants” (Section 16 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, on 6 August 2020, the City Council of Manila enacted Ordinance No. 8659, entitled: “AN ORDINANCE APPROPRIATING TWO HUNDRED MILLION PESOS (PhP. 200,000,000.00) AS SUPPLEMENTAL BUDGET NO. 13 FOR FISCAL YEAR 2020 TO COVER EXPENSES FOR COVID-19 VACCINES IN THE CITY OF MANILA”;

WHEREAS, consistent with local and national budgeting policies, such Supplemental Budget must be updated to be utilized by the City Government for fiscal year 2021;

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code, provides that: “All budgetary proposals shall be included and considered in the budget preparation process. After the local chief executive concerned shall have submitted the executive budget to the sanggunian, no ordinance providing for a supplemental budget shall be enacted, except when supported by funds actually available as certified by the local treasurer or by new revenue sources.

A supplemental budget may also be enacted in times of public calamity by way of budgetary realignment to set aside appropriations for the purchase of supplies and materials or the payment of services which are exceptionally urgent or absolutely indispensable to prevent imminent danger to, or loss of, life or property, in the jurisdiction of the local government unit or in other areas declared by the President in a state of calamity. Such ordinance shall clearly indicate the sources of funds available for appropriations, as certified under oath by the local treasurer and local accountant and attested by the local chief executive, and the various items of appropriations affected and the reasons for the change”. (Section 321 of Republic Act No. 7160); NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. The Supplemental Budget of the City Government of Manila for Fiscal Year 2021 in the amount of Two Hundred Million Pesos (PhP. 200,000,000.00) is hereby approved to re-appropriate the unutilized funds under Ordinance No. 8679 on COVID-19 vaccine expenses for Fiscal Year 2020 to Fiscal Year 2021.

SEC. 2. Source of the Fund. – The funds for the Supplemental Budget shall be sourced from funds actually available from new revenue source in the total amount of Two Hundred Million Pesos (PhP. 200,000,000.00).

SEC. 3. Use of Funds. – The amount of Two Hundred Million Pesos (PhP. 200,000,000.00) is hereby re-appropriated under the Manila Health Department (Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses - Drugs and Medicines Expenses) for the procurement of vaccines against COVID-19.

SEC. 4. Effectivity Clause. – This Ordinance shall take effect immediately upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on January 4, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8718

AN ORDINANCE AUTHORIZING THE GRANT OF GRATUITY PAY TO CONTRACT OF SERVICE AND JOB ORDER WORKERS OF THE CITY GOVERNMENT PURSUANT TO ADMINISTRATIVE ORDER NO. 38 FOR CALENDAR YEAR 2020 AND PROVIDING FUNDS THEREFOR IN THE AMOUNT OF TWENTY-NINE MILLION EIGHT HUNDRED EIGHTY-THREE THOUSAND PESOS (PhP 29,883,000.00) AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, on 28 December 2020, President Rodrigo Roa Duterte issued Administrative Order (AO) No. 38, Series of 2020, authorizing the grant of gratuity pay to contract of service (COS) and job order (JO) workers of the government for Fiscal Year (FY) 2020;

WHEREAS, as mentioned in AO No. 38, contract of service and job order “workers in the government are paid salaries/wages equivalent to the daily salaries/wages of comparable positions in government and a premium of up to 20% of such salary/wage. However, they do not enjoy benefits accorded to government employees such as the Personnel Economic Relief Allowance, Mid-Year and Year-End Bonuses, and Performance-Based Bonus, among others, considering that they have no employer-employee relationship with the government”;

WHEREAS, given this situation and in the midst of a global pandemic, the grant of a year-end gratuity pay to COS and JO workers is a well-deserved recognition of their hard work and dedication to the City;

WHEREAS, Section 5 of AO No. 38 states that “LGUs are encouraged to adopt in their respective offices the grant of gratuity pay to workers whose services are engaged through COS and JO, utilizing appropriate and available funding sources from their respective local government funds”;

WHEREAS, Section 336 of the Local Government Code provides that: “Funds shall be available exclusively for the specific purpose for which they have been appropriated. No ordinance shall be passed authorizing any transfer of appropriations from one item to another. However, the local chief executive or the presiding officer of the sanggunian concerned may, by ordinance, be authorized to augment any item in the approved annual budget for their respective offices from savings in other items within the same expense class of their respective appropriations”;

WHEREAS, earlier today, the local legislative body approved Resolution No. 36, Series of 2020, adopted by the Executive Committee of the City Development Council on 29 December 2020, entitled: "A Resolution Approving the Amendment of the Annual Investment Program and the Issuance of a Supplemental Investment Program for FY 2020 for the Grant of Gratuity Pay to Contract of Service and Job Order Workers of the City Government of Manila Pursuant to Administrative Order No. 38 for Calendar Year 2020”;

NOW, THEREFORE,
Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. Gratuity Pay.
The grant of the one-time gratuity pay for FY 2020, not exceeding Three Thousand Pesos (PhP 3,000.00), to job order and contract of service personnel of the City Government is hereby authorized, subject to the conditions under AO No. 38, s. 2020.

SECTION 2. Fund Source.
The gratuity pay in the total amount of Twenty-Nine Million Eight Hundred Eighty-Three Thousand Pesos (PhP 29,883,000.00) shall be funded by augmenting the Special Activities Fund – Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) from available savings under the FY 2020 Annual Appropriations Ordinance, detailed under Annex “A” (Statement of Funding Sources, LBP Form No. 8) and Annex “B” (Statement of Budgetary Requirement, LBP Form No. 9), which are attached and made an integral part hereof.

SECTION 3. Effectivity Clause.
This Ordinance shall have a retroactive effect as of December 29, 2020, to immediately implement AO No. 38 issued on December 28, 2020.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on January 4, 2021.

ORDINANCE NO. 8717

AN ORDINANCE AUTHORIZING THE GRANT OF SERVICE RECOGNITION INCENTIVE PURSUANT TO ADMINISTRATIVE ORDER NO. 37 FOR CALENDAR YEAR 2020 AND PROVIDING FUNDS THEREFOR IN THE AMOUNT OF NINETY-TWO MILLION EIGHT HUNDRED TWENTY THOUSAND PESOS (PhP 92,820,000.00) AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE
WHEREAS, on 28 December 2020, President Rodrigo Roa Duterte issued Administrative Order (AO) No. 38, Series of 2020, authorizing the grant of gratuity pay to contract of service (COS) and job order (JO) workers of the government for Fiscal Year (FY) 2020;

WHEREAS, as mentioned in AO No. 38, contract of service and job order “workers in the government are paid salaries/wages equivalent to the daily salaries/wages of comparable positions in government and a premium of up to 20% of such salary/wage. However, they do not enjoy benefits accorded to government employees such as the Personnel Economic Relief Allowance, Mid-Year and Year-End Bonuses, and Performance-Based Bonus, among others, considering that they have no employer-employee relationship with the government”;

WHEREAS, given this situation and in the midst of a global pandemic, the grant of a year-end gratuity pay to COS and JO workers is a well-deserved recognition of their hard work and dedication to the City;

WHEREAS, Section 5 of AO No. 38 states that “LGUs are encouraged to adopt in their respective offices the grant of gratuity pay to workers whose services are engaged through COS and JO, utilizing appropriate and available funding sources from their respective local government funds”;

WHEREAS, Section 336 of the Local Government Code provides that: “Funds shall be available exclusively for the specific purpose for which they have been appropriated. No ordinance shall be passed authorizing any transfer of appropriations from one item to another. However, the local chief executive or the presiding officer of the sanggunian concerned may, by ordinance, be authorized to augment any item in the approved annual budget for their respective offices from savings in other items within the same expense class of their respective appropriations”;

WHEREAS, earlier today, the local legislative body approved Resolution No. 36, Series of 2020, adopted by the Executive Committee of the City Development Council on 29 December 2020, entitled: "A Resolution Approving the Amendment of the Annual Investment Program and the Issuance of a Supplemental Investment Program for FY 2020 for the Grant of Gratuity Pay to Contract of Service and Job Order Workers of the City Government of Manila Pursuant to Administrative Order No. 38 for Calendar Year 2020”;

NOW, THEREFORE,
Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. Gratuity Pay.
The grant of the one-time gratuity pay for FY 2020, not exceeding Three Thousand Pesos (PhP 3,000.00), to job order and contract of service personnel of the City Government is hereby authorized, subject to the conditions under AO No. 38, s. 2020.

SECTION 2. Fund Source (Gratuity Pay).
The gratuity pay in the total amount of Twenty-Nine Million Eight Hundred Eighty-Three Thousand Pesos (PhP 29,883,000.00) shall be funded by augmenting the Special Activities Fund – Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) from available savings under the FY 2020 Annual Appropriations Ordinance, detailed under Annex “A” (Statement of Funding Sources, LBP Form No. 8) and Annex “B” (Statement of Budgetary Requirement, LBP Form No. 9), which are attached and made an integral part hereof.

SECTION 3. Fund Source (Service Recognition Incentive).
The Service Recognition Incentive in the total amount of Ninety-Two Million Eight Hundred Twenty Thousand Pesos (PhP 92,820,000.00) shall be funded by augmenting the Special Activities Fund – Personal Services Account from personal services savings under the FY 2020 Annual Appropriations Ordinance, detailed under Annex “A” (Statement of Funding Sources, LBP Form No. 8) and Annex “B” (Statement of Budgetary Requirement, LBP Form No. 9), which are attached and made an integral part hereof.

SECTION 4. Effectivity Clause.
This Ordinance shall take effect retroactively on 29 December 2020 to immediately implement AO No. 38 issued on 28 December 2020.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on December 28, 2020.

ORDINANCE NO. 8711

AN ORDINANCE AUTHORIZING THE GRANT OF THE PRODUCTIVITY ENHANCEMENT INCENTIVE TO THE EMPLOYEES OF THE CITY GOVERNMENT OF MANILA AND PROVIDING FUNDS THEREFOR FROM PERSONAL SERVICES SAVINGS AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE

WHEREAS, Executive Order No. (E.O.) 201, S. 2016, entitled: "Modifying the Salary Schedule for Civilian Government Personnel and Authorizing the Grant of Additional Benefits for both Civilian and Military and Uniformed Personnel", mandates the grant of Productivity Enhancement Incentives (PEI) to national and local government employees;

WHEREAS, as provided by E.O. 201, the PEI is meant to improve the productivity of government workers. It is granted to government workers, alongside the upward adjustment of the salary schedule in the bureaucracy;

WHEREAS, Budget Circular No. 2017-4, issued by the Department of Budget and Management (DBM), outlines the guidelines on the grant of PEI to government personnel;

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code of 1991, states that: "Every local government unit shall exercise the powers expressly granted, those necessarily implied therefrom, as well as powers necessary, appropriate, or incidental for its efficient and effective governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare. Within their respective territorial jurisdictions, local government units shall ensure and support, among other things, the preservation and enrichment of culture, promote health and safety, enhance the right of the people to a balanced ecology, encourage and support the development of appropriate and self-reliant scientific and technological capabilities, improve public morals, enhance economic prosperity and social justice, promote full employment among their residents, maintain peace and order, and preserve the comfort and convenience of their inhabitants" (Section 16 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, the same Code provides that all budgetary proposals shall be included and considered in the budget preparation process. After the local chief executive concerned shall have submitted the executive budget to the Sanggunian, no ordinance providing for a supplemental budget shall be enacted, except when supported by funds actually available as certified by the local treasurer or by new revenue sources (Section 321 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, Section 336 of the Local Government Code states that funds shall be available exclusively for the specific purpose for which they have been appropriated. No ordinance shall be passed authorizing any transfer of appropriations from one item to another. However, the local chief executive or the presiding officer of the Sanggunian concerned may, by ordinance, be authorized to augment any item in the approved annual budget for their respective offices from savings in other items within the same expense class of their respective appropriations;

WHEREAS, earlier today, the local legislative body approved Resolution No. 26, Series of 2020, adopted by the Executive Committee of the City Development Council on December 4, 2020, entitled: "A RESOLUTION APPROVING THE AMENDMENT OF THE ANNUAL INVESTMENT PROGRAM AND THE ISSUANCE OF A SUPPLEMENTAL INVESTMENT PROGRAM FOR FY 2020 FOR THE GRANT OF THE PRODUCTIVITY ENHANCEMENT INCENTIVE OF THE CITY GOVERNMENT EMPLOYEES OF THE CITY OF MANILA:"

NOW, THEREFORE, be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. Productivity Enhancement Incentive (PEI)
The PEI shall be granted to the regular, casual, and contractual employees of the City Government of Manila for Fiscal Year 2020, pursuant to DBM Budget Circular No. 2017-4 dated December 4, 2017. The Special Activities Fund-Personal Services (SAF-PS) shall be augmented for the grant of PEI in the total amount of Forty-Six Million Two Hundred Forty Thousand Pesos (PhP 46,240,000.00).

SEC. 2. Source of Funds
The funds to augment the SAF-PS for the grant of PEI shall be sourced from PS savings in the total amount of Forty-Six Million Two Hundred Forty Thousand Pesos (PhP 46,240,000.00).

SEC. 3. Effectivity Clause
This Ordinance shall take effect upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on December 7, 2020.

ORDINANCE NO. 8701

AN ORDINANCE GRANTING FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE TO JOB ORDER WORKERS, CONTRACT OF SERVICE, OR OTHER SIMILAR SCHEMES OF THE CITY GOVERNMENT OF MANILA AND PROVIDING FUNDS THEREFORE IN THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF FORTY-NINE MILLION EIGHT HUNDRED FIVE THOUSAND PESOS (PHP 49,805,000.00) AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES

PREAMBLE

WHEREAS, on March 8, 2020, Presidential Proclamation No. 922, S. 2020, was issued declaring a State of Public Health Emergency throughout the Philippines due to the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19), and the Code Alert System for COVID-19 was raised to Code Red Sublevel Two (2), in accordance with the recommendation of the Department of Health (DOH) and the Inter-Agency Task Force for the Management of Emerging Infectious Diseases;

WHEREAS, in view of the continuing rise of confirmed cases of COVID-19, the serious threat to health, safety, and security, the long-term adverse effects on livelihoods, and the severe disruption of economic activities, a state of national emergency has been declared throughout the country;

WHEREAS, these Presidential Proclamations enjoin all government agencies and Local Government Units (LGUs) to cooperate fully and mobilize the necessary resources to undertake critical and appropriate disaster response measures to address the threat of COVID-19;

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code of 1991 states that every local government unit shall exercise powers necessary for effective governance and promote general welfare, including ensuring health and safety, fostering economic prosperity, and supporting employment among residents (Section 16, Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code also provides that all budgetary proposals shall be considered during the budget preparation process and that supplemental budgets may be enacted only when supported by available funds or new revenue sources (Section 321, Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, the Code further mandates that funds must be used exclusively for their intended purposes and that any transfer of appropriations requires legislative approval (Section 336, Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, the local legislative body approved Resolution No. 20, Series of 2020, on November 20, 2020, which approved the amendment of the Annual Investment Program or issuance of a Supplemental Investment Program for FY 2020, in connection with the grant of ₱5,000 financial assistance to Job Order Workers, Contract of Service Workers, or other similar schemes under the City Government of Manila;

NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT ORDAINED by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. Financial Assistance
Financial assistance of ₱5,000 each shall be granted to Job Order Workers, Contract of Service Workers, or those under similar schemes within the City Government of Manila to help alleviate the financial burden caused by the COVID-19 crisis.

SECTION 2. Augmentation and Fund Sources
The Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) Donation Account of various departments, bureaus, and offices shall be augmented with a total amount of ₱49,805,000 from savings in various MOOE accounts under the FY 2020 Executive Budget for the purpose of providing financial assistance.

Attached are the following details:

Annex A: Declaration of Savings for Augmentation of Funds

Annex B: Budgetary Requirement for Financial Assistance

SECTION 3. Separability Clause
If any provision of this Ordinance is declared invalid or unconstitutional, the other provisions not affected thereby shall remain valid and subsisting.

SECTION 4. Effectivity Clause
This Ordinance shall take effect immediately upon approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on November 23, 2020.

ORDINANCE NO. 8673

AN ORDINANCE GRANTING INCENTIVES IN THE AMOUNT OF ONE HUNDRED THOUSAND PESOS (PHP. 100,000.00) TO ANY BARANGAY THAT SHALL REMAIN COVID-19 FREE FROM SEPTEMBER 1 TO OCTOBER 31, 2020, AS MAY BE DETERMINED BY THE MANILA HEALTH DEPARTMENT AND APPROPRIATING FUNDS THEREFORE

PREAMBLE

WHEREAS, Section 2 of Republic Act. No. 11469, provides that: "Presidential Proclamation No. 922, s. 2020, was issued declaring a State of Public Health Emergency throughout the Philippines due to the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) and the Code Alert System for COVID-19 was raised to Code Red Sublevel Two (2) in accordance with the recommendation of the Department of Health (DOH) and the Inter-Agency Task Force for the Management of Emerging Infectious Diseases.  Further, Presidential Proclamation No. 929, s. 2020, was issued declaring a State of Calamity throughout the Philippines and imposed an Enhanced Community Quarantine throughout Luzon.   

In view of the continuing rise of confirmed cases of COVID-19, the serious threat to the health, safety, security, and lives of our countrymen, the long-term adverse effects on their means of livelihood, and the severe disruption of economic activities, a state of national emergency is hereby declared over the entire country";    

WHEREAS, both Proclamations enjoined all government agencies and Local Government Units (LGUs) to render full assistance to and cooperation with each other and mobilize the necessary resources to undertake critical, urgent, and appropriate disaster response aid and measures in a timely manner to curtail and eliminate the threat of COVID-19;    

WHEREAS, Section 16 of the Local Government Code of 1991, provides that: "Every local government unit shall exercise the powers expressly granted, those necessarily implied therefrom, as well as powers necessary, appropriate, or incidental for its efficient and effective governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare.  Within their respective territorial jurisdictions, local government units shall ensure and support, among other things, the preservation and enrichment of culture, promote health and safety, enhance the right of the people to a balanced ecology, encourage and support the development of appropriate and self-reliant scientific and technological capabilities, improve public morals, enhance economic prosperity and social justice, promote full employment among their residents, maintain peace and order, and preserve the comfort and convenience of their inhabitants." (Republic Act No. 7160);    

WHEREAS, the City of Manila is made up of 896 Barangays, each of which has been mandated to implement quarantine and social distancing protocols within their jurisdictions as part of the City Government's effort to contain and delay the spread of the COVID-19 virus;    

WHEREAS, as of 22 August 2020, despite the efforts of the City Government, the total number of confirmed COVID-19 positive cases within the City of Manila has reached more than 7,500 with more than 800 active cases;    

WHEREAS, to supplement the efforts done by the national and local government agencies, as well as to promote effective and efficient local governance in times of national emergencies among barangays, the City Government undertakes to grant incentives for those barangays which shall remain COVID-19 free;    

WHEREAS, these measures shall serve as additional actions taken by the City to ensure the health and safety of its citizenry: NOW, THEREFORE,    

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. The City of Manila hereby grants One Hundred Thousand Pesos (PHP 100,000.00) as incentive to any barangay which shall remain free from COVID-19 from September 1 to October 31, 2020.    

SEC. 2. Qualifications. - To qualify for the aforesaid incentive, the barangay must meet the following criteria:    

a. That no person residing within the barangay shall be recorded as positive of the Coronavirus Disease of 2019 for a period of two (2) months starting from September 1, 2020 until October 31, 2020;  and   

b. That such data must be supported by a certification from the Manila Health Department.    

SEC. 3. Appropriation. The City Government shall appropriate funds for the implementation of this Ordinance.    

SEC. 4. Effectivity Clause. - This Ordinance shall take effect upon its approval and after publication in a newspaper of general circulation.    

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on September 3. 2020.

ORDINANCE NO. 8657

AN ORDINANCE AUTHORIZING SUPPLEMENTAL BUDGET NO. 12, THROUGH BUDGETARY REALIGNMENT, INVOLVING AN AMOUNT OF FORTY MILLION PESOS (PHP. 40,000,000.00), TO COVER EXPENSES FOR MEDICAL EQUIPMENT AND MEDICAL SUPPLIES FOR COVID-19 TESTING IN THE CITY OF MANILA

WHEREAS, Section 2 of Republic Act. No. 11469, provides that: "Presidential Proclamation No. 922, S. 2020, was issued declaring a State of Public Health Emergency throughout the Philippines due to the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) and the Code Alert System for COVID-19 was raised to Code Red Sublevel Two (2) in accordance with the recommendation of the Department of Health (DOH) and the Inter-Agency Task Force for the Management of Emerging Infectious Diseases. Further, Presidential Proclamation No. 929, S. 2020, was issued declaring a State of Calamity throughout the Philippines and imposed an Enhanced Community Quarantine throughout Luzon;

In view of the continuing rise of confirmed cases of COVID-19, the serious threat to the health, safety, security, and lives of our countrymen, the long-term adverse effects on their means of livelihood, and the severe disruption of economic activities, a state of national emergency is hereby declared over the entire country.";

WHEREAS, both Proclamations enjoined all government agencies and Local Government Units (LGUs) to render full assistance to and cooperation with each other and mobilize the necessary resources to undertake critical, urgent, and appropriate disaster response aid and measures in a timely manner to curtail and eliminate the threat of COVID-19;

WHEREAS, in the same law, the President is empowered to "ensure that all Local Government Units (LGUs) are acting within the letter and spirit of all the rules, regulations and directives issued by the National Government pursuant to the said law, and are implementing standards of Community Quarantine consistent with what the National Government has laid down for the subject area, while allowing the LGUs to continue exercising their autonomy on matters undefined by the National Government or are within the parameters it has set, and are fully cooperating towards a unified, cohesive and orderly implementation of the national policy to address COVID-19." (Section 4 (g) of RA No. 11469);

WHEREAS, the Local Government Code states that "a supplemental budget may also be enacted in times of public calamity by way of budgetary realignment to set aside appropriations for the purchase of supplies and materials or the payment of services which are exceptionally urgent or absolutely indispensable to prevent imminent danger to, or loss of, life or property, in the jurisdiction of the local government unit or in other areas declared by the President in a state of calamity. Such ordinances shall clearly indicate the sources of funds available for appropriations, as certified under oath by the local treasurer and local accountant and attested by the local chief executive, and the various items of appropriations affected and the reasons for the change." (Section 321 of Republic Act No. 7160);

WHEREAS, the Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG) and the Department of Budget and Management (DBM) had issued a Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 01, dated 27 March 2020, providing additional guidelines on the utilization of the Twenty Percent (20%) of the Annual Internal Revenue Allotment for Development Projects in view of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) situation;

WHEREAS, consequently, the following policy guidelines were provided for the Local Government Unit to comply, to wit:

"2.3 All COVID-19 related expenses to be funded by the LGUs should be part of their respective approved AIPs. In case the COVID-19-related expenses are not among those included in the approved AIP, the local development council shall prepare a supplemental investment program for the purpose, to be approved by the local sanggunian.

2.4. In case the LGUs opt to realign their existing PPAs under the 20% DF, including the continuing appropriations from previous years' 20% DF, for COVID-19-related expenses as authorized under this JMC, the LGUs concerned shall effect changes in their respective annual budgets through the following: a. Changes in annual budgets through supplemental budgets in accordance with Section 321 of the Code and Article 417 of its IRR, as amended by Administrative Order No. 47. S. 1993;"

WHEREAS, earlier today, the local legislative body approved Resolution No. 12, Series of 2020, adopted by the Executive Committee of the City Development Council on July 24, 2020, entitled: "A RESOLUTION APPROVING RESOLUTION NO. 12, SERIES OF 2020, PASSED BY THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE OF THE CITY DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL ON JULY 24, 2020 ENTITLED "A RESOLUTION APPROVING THE AMENDMENT OF THE ANNUAL INVESTMENT PROGRAM OR ISSUANCE OF A SUPPLEMENTAL INVESTMENT PROGRAM FOR FY 2020 IN CONNECTION WITH THE CITY OF MANILA'S ACTION PLAN AGAINST COVID-19 SPECIFICALLY THE PROVISION FOR: (A) MEDICAL, DENTAL AND LABORATORY SUPPLIES EXPENSES IN THE AMOUNT OF TWENTY MILLION PESOS (PHP. 20,000,000.00) FOR COVID-19 TESTING REAGENTS; (B) COVID-19 LABORATORY TESTING EXPENSES IN THE AMOUNT OF TEN MILLION PESOS (PHP. 10,000,000.00); AND (C) MEDICAL EQUIPMENT IN THE AMOUNT OF TEN MILLION PESOS (PHP. 10,000,000.00)": NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT;

SECTION 1. The Supplemental Budget of the City Government of Manila for Fiscal Year 2020 in the amount of Forty Million Pesos (PhP. 40,000,000.00) is hereby approved.

SEC. 2. Source of Funds. - The source of funds for the Supplemental Budget in the total amount of Forty Million Pesos (PhP. 40,000,000.00) shall be derived from the following sources:

a. 20% City Development Fund 
a.1. Public Health Laboratory 
PHP 40,000,000.00

SEC. 3. Use of Funds. - The amount of Forty Million Pesos (PhP. 40,000,000.00) is hereby appropriated for the Supplemental Budget of the City Government of Manila under the Manila Health Department with the following appropriations:

1. Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) under Medical, Dental and Laboratory Supplies Expenses in the amount of Twenty Million Pesos (PhP. 20,000,000.00) for Covid-19 Testing Reagents;

2. MOOE under Other Maintenance and Operating Expenses in the amount of Ten Million Pesos (PhP. 10,000,000.00) for Covid-19 Laboratory Testing; and

3. Capital Outlay under Medical Equipment in the amount of Ten Million Pesos (PhP. 10,000,000.00) for various medical equipment.

SEC. 4. Effectivity Clause. - This Ordinance shall take effect immediately upon its approval.

This Ordinance was finally enacted by the City Council of Manila on July 27, 2020.

ORDINANCE NO. 8654

AN ORDINANCE ADOPTING CERTAIN ZONING REGULATIONS RESPONSIVE TO
THE "NEW NORMAL AND PROVIDING FOR ITS ADMINISTRATION AND
ENFORCEMENT THEREBY AMENDING THE CITY ORDINANCE NO 8119.
OTHERWISE KNOWN AS THE MANILA COMPREHENSIVE LAND USE PLAN AND
ZONING ORDINANCE OF 2006

PREAMBLE

WHEREAS, on March 16, the National Government imposed an enhanced community quarantine (ECQ) over the entire Luzon due to the pandemic brought about by the threat of the coronavirus disease (COVID-19);

WHEREAS, even as the National Government gradually modified the status of the community quarantine in the National Capital Region (NCR), from ECQ to MECQ to GCQ, and prepares to lift the GCQ, there is the realization that things will never be the same again, which constitutes the need to transcend into the "New Normal";

WHEREAS, to help the local economy to build back better and maximize the ease- of-doing business in the city, leniency of certain zoning regulations and respective documentary requirements shall be herein-adopted. In any case, the leniencies shall not be detrimental to the health, safety and welfare of the people in the community and shall cause no adverse impact to the subject site/place and its adjacent neighborhood;

WHEREAS, in order to implement policies and programs adapting to a "new normal" state of economic activities, the City Government of Manila recognizes the need to adopt certain zoning regulations responsive to the "New Normal", thereby pump- priming the local economy while providing the proper regulatory environment within the framework of good governance and community participation: NOW, THEREFORE,

Be it ordained by the City Council of Manila, in session assembled, THAT:

SECTION 1. Title of the Ordinance. - An ordinance adopting certain zoning regulations responsive to the "new normal" and providing for its administration and enforcement thereby amending the City Ordinance No. 8119, otherwise known as "The Manila Comprehensive Land Use Plan and Zoning Ordinance of 2006".

SEC. 2. Purposes. - Manila's complexity as a highly urbanized city with the highest population density in the world, serving as center of culture, educations, services and trade, the proposed amendment to the allowable and restricted uses stipulated in the existing Zoning Ordinance is envisioned to be more resilient, effective and responsive to the current urban challenges posed by its unique nature and characteristics which sets it apart from other cities in the Metro.

ARTICLE II, AUTHORITY AND PURPOSE - Sec. 12 and Sec. 15 and ARTICLE VIII Sec. 52, ARTICLE XI - Sec. 78 is hereby supplemented and shall henceforth be read as follows:

ARTICLE II
AUTHORITY AND PURPOSE

SEC. 12. Use Regulations in High Density Residential/Mixed Use Zone (R3-MXD). An R-3/MXD shall be primarily for high-density high- rise housing/dwelling purposes and limited complementary/supplementary trade, services and business activities. Enumerated below are the allowable uses:

1. Detached family dwelling;
2. Semi-detached family dwelling e.g. duplex, row houses;
3. Multi-family dwelling;
4. Commercial housing E.g. hotel, apartment, apartelle, boarding house, dormitory, pension house, club house, motel, residential inn;
5. Branch library, art gallery and exhibit area;
6. Pro school and tutorial centers, provided that they do not exceed four (4) classrooms;
7. Home-based businesses, including, but not limited to dressmaking, tailoring, baking, gourmet food-making, sari-sari store, provided that:
a. The number of persons engaged in such business/industry shall not exceed three (3), inclusive of the owner; 
b. The area shall not occupy more than 20% of the total floor area of the dwelling unit and there shall be no change in the outside appearance of the building or premises; 
c. No home-based shall be conducted in any customary accessory uses cited-above; 
d. No traffic shall be generated by such home-based in greater volume than would be normally expected in a residential neighborhood and any need for parking generated by the conduct of such home occupation shall be met off the street, sidewalk and in a place other than in a declared parking space of the business owner; 
e. No equipment or process shall be used in such home-based which creates noise, vibration, glare, fumes, odor, or electrical interference detectable to the normal senses and visual or audible interference in any radio television receivers or causes fluctuation in the line voltage of the premises;
8. Home industry classified as cottage industry or small-scale industry which does not require heavy equipment as defined by DTI provided that: 
a. Such home industry shall not occupy more than thirty percent (30%) of the floor area of the dwelling unit in order to maintain its residential use or fifty Square Meters (50 Sq. M.), whichever is lesser. There shall be no change or alteration in the outside appearance of the dwelling unit and shall not be a nuisance/hazard; 
b. Allotted capitalization shall not exceed the capitalization as set by the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI); 
c. Shall consider same provisions as enumerated in letter c, d & e of Home occupation of this section;
9. Multi-purpose Hall & Barangay Hall with parking provision within the building;
10. Nursing/convalescent home;
11. Philanthropic or charitable institution;
12. Plant nursery, retail of plants, grass, garden accessories, etc. (neighborhood-scale operation);
13. Sale of aquarium fish, pet animals, foods and accessories;
14. Fire and security station;
15. Office (consultancy, legal, accountancy, brokerage, custom brokerage, funeral, sales, etc.) provided that there is no actual display, sale, transfer or lending of the office commodities in the premise;
16. Transport and ticketing office, travel agency (with minimum business area of thirty Square Meters (30 Sq. M.);
17. General retail store (not shopping center) E.g. bookstore, school and office supply, photo shop, flower shop, drug store, souvenir shop, RTWs, cellphone shop & accessories;
18. Retail of bicycle and accessories;
19 Party needs (balloons, favors, decorations, toys, etc.);
20. Food markets and shops 
E g. bakery, bake shop, wine store, water refilling station, mini-grocery, convenient store, frozen meat;
21. Personal services shops 
E.g. beauty parlor, barber shop, spa (provided it shall not exceed two rooms), dressmaking, tailoring shops (provided that machines are limited to four (4) units), laundry and steam/dry cleaning outlets (except industrial in nature), embroidery with two (2) unit machines;
22. Parks, garden, playgrounds, sports-related/recreational center/establishments 
E.g. play court, swimming pool, community gymnasium, entertainment and amusement centers;
23. Food stalls and eateries;
24. Restaurant, canteen or food-serving establishment;
25. Short-term special education/training (eg. personality development, dancing schools, schools for self-defense, driving schools, speech clinics, computer/internet centers);
26. Storeroom (but use only as an ancillary for the efficient conduct of the business);
27. Filling station/service station provided that the location should be at least two hundred Meters (200 M.) away from institutions such as school, church, hospital, etc. and with approved Special Use Permit;
28. Petroleum dealer/fuel hauler office (provided that there is a legitimate parking space in a C3-MXD Zone);
29. Manpower agency (with minimum area of one hundred Square Meters (100 Sq. M.) as per DOLE);
30. Messengerial service, janitorial service;
31. Installation services (telecommunication, CCTV, electrical, n.e.c.);
32. Security and talent agency;
33. Bank, finance, insurance, remittance center, pawnshop, bayad center, money exchange service and other financial institutions;
34. Radio and television station, media service without antennae;
35. Printing Activity: Photocopy, typing and desktop printing only;
36. Gaming and internet café provided that the location is at least two hundred Meters (200 M.) away from the institutions such as school, church, hospital;
37. Repair of optical instruments and equipment and cameras;
38. Repair of clocks and watches;
39. Manufacture of insignia, badges and similar emblems except metal;
40. Carwash, auto-detailing and vulcanizing shop with a minimum business space consideration of thirty Square Meters (30 Sq. M.) and frontage width not less than five Square Meters (5 Sq M.) (extension of business activity on sidewalk and city road is ground for the revocation of zoning permit);
41. Single parking slot for taxi, PUJ, small van, mini-school bus for single unit provided that there is a legitimate parking space and not obstructing on city roads and sidewalk;
42. Scientific, cultural and academic centers and research facilities except nuclear, radio-active, chemical and biological warfare facilities;
